article.description: Jeff Horner and Greg Brunner each scored 16 points to lead No. 20 Iowa to an 86-41 victory over Maryland-Eastern Shore in the first round of the Guardians Classic.
article.headline: Horner, Brunner spark Iowa rout of Md.-Eastern Shore
article.linkText: Horner, Brunner spark Iowa rout of Md.-Eastern Shore
article.story:
IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- As seniors and four-year starters, Greg Brunner and Jeff Horner are expected to set the tone for Iowa this season.

The duo did just that Monday night.

Horner and Brunner each scored 16 points, led fast breaks and grappled on the floor for loose balls in the early minutes to lead the No. 20 Hawkeyes to an 86-41 victory over Maryland-Eastern Shore in the opening round of the Guardians Classic.

"I thought our leadership was tremendous," Iowa coach Steve Alford said. "At the start of the game it was very good, and at the start of the second half it was very good. It's a great way to start a tournament."

Iowa advanced to play Tuesday against Colgate, which beat Utah Valley State 55-42.

Adam Haluska added 12 points and Mike Henderson 10 for the Hawkeyes, who never trailed and shot 51 percent from the floor in coasting to their 28th straight season-opening victory. They have won 42 home openers in a row.

Maryland-Eastern Shore, which started three freshmen and has five others on its roster, made mistakes typical of a young, inexperienced team. The Hawks committed 25 turnovers in their opener and struggled in transition to keep pace with Iowa's relentless, up-tempo style.

The Hawks were led by junior college transfer Antonio McMillion, who had 14 points. Tim Parham, one of their two seniors, added 11 points and 11 rebounds. The Hawks shot only 27 percent -- and just 11 percent from behind the 3-point line.

"Did I see anything positive? No," second-year coach Larry Lessett said. "We have freshmen and that monster showed its head tonight. But I don't think we are as bad as the score says."

After a slow start, Iowa found its rhythm and pulled away in the first half. The Hawkeyes went on a 26-8 run behind 15 points from Horner and Brunner, who were among several veterans Alford challenged after lackluster performances in Iowa's two exhibition wins.

"Coach thought we didn't come out strong" in the exhibitions, said Horner, who added seven assists and three steals. "Us seniors kind of took it upon ourselves to make sure everybody was ready. And we came out well tonight and played very well defensively."

The Hawkeyes pressured Maryland-Eastern Shore throughout the first half, forcing 14 turnovers to build a 44-20 lead at halftime.

In the second half, Iowa continued to pull away, outmuscling the Hawks down low and pushing the ball up court at every opportunity to build a 30-point lead just five minutes into the second half.

Several players fueled Iowa's fast-paced tempo, but freshman Tony Freeman flashed his potential for energizing the offense throughout the game. In the first half, Freeman thrilled the crowd on a fast break when he threw the ball off the backboard and Doug
Thomas, trailing on the play, grabbed the ball in mid air and slammed it through the hoop.

"I talk fast. I stutter sometimes when I talk too fast," said Freeman, who finished with seven points and six assists. "I'm trying to learn to slow down, but it's just in me."

Iowa outrebounded the Hawks 47-36, nearly doubled their point production in the paint and scored 16 fast-break points. Iowa also had 17 steals and eight blocked shots.
